  • Decrease of fixations duration with increasing age
  • Lower attention times at 12 months
  • Lower mean maps at 5 months (means there is more variability in the gaze location from one child to another)
  • Comparable times of reaction to novelty
  • Comparable levels of eye looking (maybe lower at 24m, needs formally testing)
  • Reaction times decrease with increasing age

6 Note on model diagnostics

All model diagnostics are founs in a separate document model_diagnostics.html

7 Models without exposure

Regarding model diagnostics:

  • Residuals overall OK, maybe not so good for looking time and percent eyes. We may want to interpret these two indicators with more care.

  • Confirms relationships with child age previously observed in the descriptive boxplots, for all scores except reaction to novelty
  • No significant association for reaction to novelty
  • Associations between sex and looking time (higher for girls) and reaction time (lower for girls)
  • Associations between maternal age and reaction time (increases with maternal age) and fixation duration (increases with maternal age)
  • All associations very similar for reaction time and fixation duration

8 Pregnancy mean

8.1 Pregnancy mean - relationship shape

Check annex for plots/values.

Suspected associations:

  • Looking time: MBzP, MEP, MnBP non linear
  • Reaction to novelty: DEHP and ohMPHP non linear
  • Percent eyes: DiNP non linear

=> will present tertile models for at least:

  • Looking time VS MBzP, MEP, MnBP VS
  • Percent eyes VS DiNP

8.2 Pregnancy mean - final model

  • Fixation duration: negative association with MBzP
  • Looking time: positive association with DINCH, MBzP, MEP
  • Percent eyes: negative association with DiNP
  • Reaction to novelty: positive associations with DEHP and ohMPHP

=> associations in same direction within scores

9 T2 exposure

9.1 T2 exposure - relationship shape

Check annex for plots/values.

  • Looking time: DEHP, MiBP non linear
  • Reaction to novelty: MnBP non linear
  • Reaction time: MBzP linear

=> will present tertile models for at least:

  • Looking time VS DEHP and MiBP
  • Reaction to novelty and MnBP

9.2 T2 exposure - final model

  • Fixation duration: negative association with MBzP, MiBP
  • Looking time: positive association with DINCH, MiBP and negative association with MBzP
  • Reaction to novelty: positive associations with MnBP

10 T3 exposure

10.1 T3 exposure - relationship shape

Check annex for plots/values.

  • Fixation duration: MnBP linear
  • Looking time: MEP, MnBP non linear
  • Mean map: DiNP linear
  • Reaction to novelty: MEP, MnBP non linear
  • Reaction time: DEHP, DiNP non linear

10.2 T3 exposure - final model

  • Fixation duration: negative association with MBzP
  • Looking time: positive association with DEHP, MEP and MnBP
  • Reaction time: negative associations with DEHP, DiNP, MnBP
  • Reaction to novelty: negative associations with MEP positive association with MnBP

11 All models

Combination of all previous models in one single plot in order to check consistency between T2, T3 and their mean.

By score:

  • Fixation duration: linear negative association with MBzP (all periods) and linear negative association with T2 exposure to MiBP
  • Looking time: need to do more careful model diagnostic before interpretation (see remark on model residuals for this score) + I have some concerns on the validity of this score (not actually developed to measure the quality of the attention which may produce more noisy results)
  • Mean map: no association
  • Percent eyes: need to do more careful model diagnostic before interpretation (see remark on model residuals for this score)
  • Reaction time: negative association DEHP and DiNP second tertile in T3 + linear negative association with T3 exposure to MnBP
  • Reaction to novelty: negative association MEP 2nd T3 tertile, positive associations MnBP both T2 tertiles and MnBP second T3 tertile, positive associations MEP 2nd T3 tertile, positive association ohMPHP 2nd pregnancy tertile and DEHP both pregnancy tertiles.
